</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Bertoxxulous, you are his subjects and followers.. not that much is know about him as he is not solid in game as far as i know, from what i have learnt he is a half human half skeleton/zombie partially crippled human with a charismatic smile and confident voice... He sounds like a worthy leader able to lead his troops and followers the way he wishes to go... so maybe he will take extreem anger on this compared to the other deitys, or maybe he will call in his debts and just make you serve in undeath... who knows.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>There's actually plenty of source material on Bertoxxulous ever since Verant did the Karanas Plague a few months ago. <br><br>The philosophy around Bertoxxulous is centered on an unreputable and unbreakable Law of Nature and Law of Physics -- all things will decay in due time, all things will eventually break down in due time, all things of order will eventually break down into disorder in due time. <br><br>In physics, this is called the Law of Entropy. Anyone who has taken high school or college physics knows about this. <br><br>Thus the philosophy of Bertoxxulous and his followers are simply stressing the darker side (and unpleasant side) of the natural laws of balance.  Those of the goodly alignments see this decay and deterioration as something perverse and evil. Yet there is nothing untruthful about it..... it's a normal part of the balance of nature. <br><br>Perhaps what makes Bertoxxulous &quot;evil&quot; is the fact that his power (as a deity) thrives on this natural process of decay, and that his followers are encouraged to &quot;accelerate&quot; this process of decay and entropy. <br><br>As for the relation between Bertoxxulous and his followers.... it's quite simple, really:  <br><br>1) Every mortal will eventually fall to the natural process of death, decay, and decomposition. <br><br>2) Bertoxxulous' power thrives on this process, thus his followers are encouraged to speed up this process. <br><br>3) In return for their loyalty, especially for the necromantic followers..... Bertoxxulous promises them life after death.... in essence, he promises them undead immortality as a way to CHEAT the natural process. <br><br>4) In essence, Bertoxxulous plays favorites with the mortals. Those who oppose him will suffer the fate of death and decay, where they deserve to be cursed with sickness and disease and suffering and once they die they will be nothing more than the worthless soil in the earth. Yet those mortals who are loyal to Bertoxxulous have a chance to be promised immortality...... undeath.... undead life. As far as the most successful necromancers are concerned, this is what is considered Lichdom. <br><br>In most fantasy games like D&amp;D, Lichdom is cited as the ultimate form of undead, it's a form of near-immortality.....oftentimes portrayed as stronger than a vampire. It's also an EQ spell of course.... tho the spell is nowhere as impressive as the original mythical concept of the Lich undead. <br><br>So those who serve the Plaguebringer are nowhere near self-destructive. They are not suicidal people, nor do they look forward to dying very soon. They have a lot of work ahead of them.... and often times, they know that their work is hindered by the diametrically opposed powers of life and growth (Tunare, Karana, Rodcet Nife) <br><br>Ever wonder why Bertoxxulous worshippers are default alignment Discordant Evil?  It all comes back to entropy (disorder).  Verant actually had this one well thought out. <br><br>/end lecture<br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ugoestwoodwalker.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Goest Woodwalker</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(1/23/02 10:33:0